segments.text: Nice bright day in College Station.
Had the pleasure of chatting with Harrison Hurth, fellow Presbyterian, and a dear friend about his experiences here at College Station.
This is February 15, 1999, a bright sunny day.
Have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Harrison Hurth.

Before we start talking about A&M, so that anyone in the future might know a little bit about your background before A&M, give us a brief biographical summary of your experience before coming to College Station.
Okay.
Well, I was born in Pontiac, Illinois, and I lived there through high school.
I went to undergraduate school at Illinois Western University in Bloomington, Illinois, where I met my wife, Margaret Rowland, and married her in 1938.
I went then to the University of Illinois for a master's degree, and I taught for a number of years in Illinois high school.
It's in Clinton, Illinois.
I came to A&M when the University of Illinois placement office sent me a notice that A&M wanted some teachers for summer school.
That didn't sound like a summer resort, and I thought, well, that's a chance to give the collegiate level a shot.
So I applied.
What year was that?
That was 1946.
And Dr. Thomas Mayo replied and said he didn't meet anyone after all,
He probably would be contacting me in the fall, but maybe not quite that strong, but something between a possibility and a polite brush off.
And I think on the Fourth of July weekend, I was visiting some friends in Western Illinois, and he had called me prior to that, and I talked it over with him, and he crashed around.
He had made me an offer.
So I called on that weekend, and I arrived a week late in September 1946.
My younger daughter had just been born and was not really doing too well.
Margaret was still in the hospital.
I came down alone, and someone had been covering for me for a week or so.
I'd be interested, you came by car?
Came by car.
And what, how much gear did you bring in that car?
Well, what I had was a 1938 Chevrolet Coupe.
They didn't have a very big truck, but I obviously bought enough stuff to survive because I had enough clothing to last until Thanksgiving, when I got my wife at Thanksgiving time.
And then y'all drove by.
Was that your only car?
Yeah, what happened this time, the relative drove Margaret and her mother to Memphis.
I went to Memphis on the train, and we drove back then in her mother's car.
And where were you all living then?
Well, we lived out to A&M Annex.
The University College had taken over Lowe-Bine Air Base and turned it into the A&M Annex.
We had an apartment in what had been an officer's ward in the hospital.
That scared me.
I was going to bring a new baby down.
I spent every evening with an old Dutch cleanser scrubbing down the walls.
We had a large room big enough for a square dance in front, which we did not use in the apartment behind it.
We had, I don't know, four or five radiators, two or three commodes.
And was this furnished?
Yes.
What kind of furniture was in it?
Well, no I'm sorry, it was not furnished.
That's another story.
We did burn our furniture.
And when the furniture truck drove up, the driver demanded $700, which I hadn't counted.
A lot of money then.
I didn't have $700.
So I hot-footed it into the First National Bank and talked to Travis Bryant.
Got $700 and have banked with him ever since.
I can imagine
how that would be important.
That air base experience, I think, is very, very important.
That story about what was the enrollment and the out there and the faculty.
How many folks were there?
Well, 1946 was the year the veterans came.
And the enrollment of the college virtually doubled.
Yes, probably the total moment must have been in the area of 7,000.
And they put a freshman class.
All freshmen?
All freshmen.
What would that be?
And some of those were veterans and some were not.
Is that right?
I'm not sure whether veterans went to the annex or not.
I'm really not sure.
All right, so you're implying that most of them- Most of them are- Right out of high school.
Right out of high school, yeah.
They had the whole setup.
They had military personnel out there to have a core.
They set up a campus post office.
They had a student center.
Dr. Harrington and John Paul Abbott at different times, whatever the title was, I believe they called them deans.
and directed the operation.
And you offered the full range of courses for freshmen.
Did any of them come into the main campus to take any courses?
I don't believe so.
Our faculty people taught both classes.
I taught mostly on the main campus, actually.
And those of us who did carpool,
And I had a semester or two when I taught a couple of days at the annex and three other times.
Describe the students and their capability.
Well, I dealt largely with the veterans.
I did teach freshman at the annex, as I said, a couple days a week, a semester or two.
But I dealt very largely with the veterans.
And of course, they were excellent students.
Do you remember any anecdotes or examples of that purpose and determination on their part?
Any of them ever say anything or do anything that illustrated that?
One thing that surprised me, quite a few of those fellows went into the Cold War.
I would have thought, you know, that they had all the military they wanted, but a very precise number of them went into the Cold War.
And their academic performance was very good.
Were there instances when you could sense that the experience of where they'd been and what they'd seen
helped them to understand something that you were trying to teach them?
Well, I'm sure that happened, but I really don't remember any specifics.
Obviously, we knew they were around.
What was your teaching load?
What courses and how many?
We taught 18 hours, for goodness sake.
Freshman composition, of course, and the sophomore literature course.
I took that, I taught that, I taught a shift for the course.
About what was the enrollment per section?
I guess it was pretty close to 30.
But no big sections?
No big sections.
No, I don't think there were.
And you gave them the same kind of assignments and homework that you would have any other classes?
Pretty much.
What about their attendance?
Is it regular?
Regular.
Let's go back to the air base.
There are many hundreds of students out there.

and almost all of their activities were out there i know that's when the fish drill team was created and i understand there was a freshman band what interaction was there between the main campus of the students and the air base well actually uh
Well, they went to town on weekends and all that kind of thing.
Actually, it wasn't all that much.
I think the sophomores were very unhappy that they weren't getting out the freshmen as they might have liked.
Well, was there any hazing out there?
No.
Because there were only freshmen?
Only freshmen.
Now, about how many of you faculty lived out there?
Well, let's see.
There must have been 30 or 40 families.
There was a housing area near the entrance called The Village, and a group lived up there.
And the rest of us were in barracks apartments.
And I don't know if you know these people or not.
the Lee Martins and the Staley Cresswells and the Ed Holdridges and the C.K.
Estins and the Vance Sumner in economics.
Vance and I put out a garden together one spring and I started digging first and I did cut one end of it.
Vance showed up one day and said, now's the time to start our garden.
I'll take this.
So I had to dig up the other end.
And you did garden.
Did many others garden out there?
Yeah, there were several gardens.
We had a pretty nice life out there, really.
We had a swimming pool.
We had a baseball diamond.
We were working.
I just wanted to be sure it was turning.
Yeah.
We...
had all those miles of barracks for the kids to go skate in.
Great place for kids.
Was there any hazing of the freshmen?
I don't think so.
Because there were no sophomores.
No sophomores there, no.
But they were organized in military fashion.
They ate together.
Not many of them had cars.
That's true.
Yeah, I remember that mess all night.
They kidded me.
I came down here from Illinois, and one of the first meals we had, I said, you know, I don't like beans, but these are the best beans I ever ate.
Black-eyed peas.
Never heard of them.
So you all dined in the old base mess hall.
Did you faculty members eat in the dining hall, or did you eat on your own at home?
Well, I ate in the dining hall until I got my family.
And most people did.
Describe the faculty social life between you faculty families that were out there.
Well, there was an article in the paper not too long ago that you might have seen about my wife and her bridge club.
They organized a bridge club out there that's still going.
and got together and played cards and we played some softball with the garden and swam.
We didn't really have, well we might have used the student center, actually didn't have much of a place to get together as a group.
We got very close as neighbors.
The, and you said that Dr. Harrington
and or John Paul were administratively responsible for?
Yes, at different times.
Dr. Harrington started and at some point he moved on to John Paul Abbott.
Now did that have, what was the official title of that unit?
Was it Texas A&M?
Oh, the whole unit.
Texas A&M Annex.
Annex, okay.
And you were out there how long?
Four years.
Four?
Oh, I didn't know it was that long.
We moved, well, three actually.
We moved here and actually four now.
And most others stayed one more year.
So then that lasted from...
46 to 50, the interim period between World War II and Vietnam.
I mean, and Korean War.
Right.
And the Korean War.
Back to, what was your beginning faculty salary?
I believe it was $2,250.
For nine months.
Well, actually, most of us got one and a half.
Well, but I'm assuming that was the base.
Yeah, that was nine months.
And you and your wife had two daughters at that point.
Was there an elementary school out there for those that were school age?
Well, our older daughter was school age, and she went to some advanced school.
Oh!
Little country school.
Little country school.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
And it started there in the first grade.
And she came home one day and said, I know the first grade boys, the second grade boys, those third grade boys are hard.
Came back crying one day, said she had to show us her report card.
My A has it marked black, nobody else had it.
Oh, it was a plus.
Uh-oh, I was going to say.
She was there, I think, two years and then went to Bowie School.
All right, as you look back on it, how did those two years, were those good years for her?
Yes.
She had a splendid teacher, one she loved, and they were good years.
All right, so you taught out there.
Three years.
Then you moved to this house?
Yes.
And that's 1949.
And what's the address of this house?
208 Fairview Avenue.
Okay.
Describe the neighborhood when you all moved in.
What was Southside like?
Well, really, it was pretty bare.
This house was built by a lady in extension named Jenny Camp.
She built this house with two plugs next door and one across the corner.
And this was a prayer ring.
Some of the men in the extension thought she was going to lose her shirt, so they formed a committee to try to get this away.
But Miss Jenny went ahead and did all right.
Then, I don't know much about this, but shortly thereafter, there was a group of faculty people
I'm not even sure who they were, but they formed what they called the corporation and they built the good money houses on the streets and they began to fill in for the trees.
Were there any native trees on these blocks?
We have a native juju tree.
And this area is, am I correct, that it was called Southside or Southgate?
College Park.
College Park.
Oh, okay.
Were there some older houses east of us, just south of what used to be called Jersey?
Yes.
All right.
You all move here.
The girls grow up here, your two daughters.
And you then, did you teach a fourth year out at the Air Base, or did you start teaching full-time here on the campus that fourth year?
I began teaching full-time.
About how big was the English department in numbers of faculty?
Oh, they had hired a good many.
Motley Crue also, because of the influx of veterans.
I suppose we had 50 maybe.
Who were, let's try to recall as many of those as you can, who were some of the senior English faculty when you arrived?
Well, Dr. Mayo headed the department, Dr. Morgan was here, Dr. Abbott, John Paul Abbott.
Ernest Hitchcock.
Nolan Shepard.
Bird Price.
All right, let's go back.
Louis Hauer.
Louis Hauer.
Let's go back.
Describe Dr. Mayo for someone that may never have met him.
Well he's a very charming man.
Very lively and articulate and learned and cordial.
He just exuded charm.
He was a great conversationalist.
He couldn't bear a moment of silence.
Now he was the department head?
Yes, he had been moved over from the library.
He had been a librarian and I think really that was his first love.
And y'all, the department office in the academic building?
In the academic building.
Which floors?
Third.
Third.
How many floors are there?
We were just below the architects.
All right, they were on the, I think they're the fourth or the fifth, whatever it is.
Yeah, so we were on the floor below them, whatever that was.
I remember later when I was going over every night trying to write a dissertation, my wife would worry about me, and I said, go over there and load the office up.
Never alone.
Let's see.
Dr. Abbott.
Describe him.
Very dapper.
Very dapper little fellow.
I think the students called him Jelly Abbott.
Now he became a dean, didn't he?
Yes.
He did.
He served as the dean of liberal arts briefly.
He spent one year on the court.
And then he became a distinguished professor.
What was his specialty?
Well, no, it's strange.
I don't think he ever published.
Oh, okay.
Let's see, did Dr. Mayo have a nickname?
Did students give him a nickname?
If he did, I didn't.
I never knew him.
Dr. Morgan, let's go to him.
Yeah, Bloody.
Bloody Morgan.
Bloody Morgan.
And he would later be department head, wouldn't he?
Yes, he was.
Describe him.
Well, he was short, stocky, bald-headed, a bit dogmatic, pretty much knew it all, excellent golfer, and played baseball at
Ohio State, I believe, had a big league tryout, which didn't materialize.
At least he had the tryout.
He described himself as a scholar with, he said, a foul man's body.
Now, not many of those senior colleagues were Texans, were they?
It all came from a wide variety of... John Paul was from Tennessee.
What's the university in Nashville?
Vanderbilt.
Vanderbilt.
Hedgecock was in Tennessee.
Mayo?
Yeah, through Mayo.
I really don't know.
I'm not sure I know.
Because...
In some of the other areas, I know there were lots of Aggies.
And you started working on your doctoral degree when?
I was in Wisconsin in 53 and 54.
So you took leave?
Took leave, yeah.
And did you take wife and daughters with you?
Oh, yes, I did.
And the housing was tight at the University of Wisconsin.
And we lived in a trailer just
across from the field house, actually, and the stadium, is it called?
I'll think, maybe I'll think of it.
I can't think what the, what that trailer area was called.
Something Park, I believe.
And anyhow, we had a trailer with an oil heater for heat, no running water.
all the water and bathhouses.
Actually, we were comfortable.
They had the thing organized.
They had a
We were all graduate students.
They had a body that took charge of the thing, and we had to get permission to get a larger trailer and bring our father and daughter.
We went up with our younger daughter only, leaving our older daughter, Mary Margaret, in the school in Lexington, Illinois with her grandmother until we could.
They gave us permission to get a bigger trailer.
We were on the right side of town.
They went to the best schools in the city.
Mary Margaret took West Isaac.
We'd forgotten the elementary school.
They were on the right side of town.
We were actually very comfortable.
The kids would go down the night that Margaret worked to help put me through.
Actually, she worked for the Wisconsin General Hospital.
And she worked nights as a nurse's aide.
And I was along with the kids.
Well, the girls would go down to the bathhouse, take their shower.
They'd hide in stalls and listen to the young ladies talk about their babies and whatnot.
I frequently had to go rust out some woman to go down and get them out.
Now, did A&M give you a leave of absence?
Yes.
So you knew you had a slot coming back.
Yes.
And the...
You funded all of this entirely yourself?
Yes, we had saved, and we rented the house, and we had the same record, but we spent too long to make it.
I got a letter from Travis Bryan when I was there.
You couldn't believe I'd been there that long, didn't need some money.
He wrote me this dear friend Harrison letter.
I can't quote it anymore, but it was in his famous style.
Right, and then you came back then and finished your dissertation a little later, and your special area was what?
And I, yes, I finished all the coursework and passed my qualifying and all that stuff.
And came back and wrote the dissertation.
Went back to my office every night and wrote it.
Came home one night, wondered, how many pages did you write?
I said, I didn't write any, and I sadly bought it.
She didn't approve of that.
All right, during the 50s, what were the changes here at A&M?
During what?
During the 50s.
Oh.
What were the changes here at A&M?
The moment goes down a little as the veterans go on.
Not one thing.
Well, one thing I remember from that time, the computers came along.
We had our first computer center somewhere in the early 50s.
And the first study done on the thing was one by Charlie Hagelman, who was head of Lamar.
I remember the subject, but that's his first name.
And then Milton Huggins did a concordance to the Book of Common Prayer, and a student,
When y'all come back, the students, generalize about the students and what their interests were in the 50s.
Were there many English majors, many social sciences, humanities students at A&M then?
Not many.
I don't know how many majors.
Yeah, we did that.
The typical student taking one of your advanced courses, taking it as an elective?
We had some who did that.
Those who did were good students.
Do you recall any pranks or jokes or incidents in classes where the students figured out some kind of something or other?
Anybody ever pull one off in class on you?
Very likely.
I don't really know.
All right.
Now, your nickname, I understand, was Happy.
Yeah, I think I discovered they called me Happy Harry.
Do you know when you discovered that?
I don't know.
I don't remember how I found it out.
Now, let's stay with these nicknames a little.
Mr. Coffers, D.B.
Coffers.
Dusty Butt.
Dusty Butt.
Bloody Morgan.
Bloody Morgan.
Did Huggett have a nickname?
I don't believe so.
If so, I didn't know it.
Any others you remember in English or anywhere else?
Well, elsewhere, of course, Square Root Jackson.
Mm-hmm.
And Alphabet Thompson.
Dr. Dan the Grade Point Man.
All right.
Oh, Jock Woods.
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
OK, now I anoint you as a philosopher.
What did those nicknames really mean?
Why did students come up with those?
Oh, I think it was affection, maybe.
I agree with you.
They weren't mean.
Not at all.
Maybe perfection may be too strong.
I don't know.
But they weren't mean.
I think it was kind of affection and respect.
Now, correct me if I'm wrong.
They did not ever intentionally use those.
